The '''County Borough of Leeds''' and the preceeding '''Municipal Borough of Leeds''' was a local government district in the [[West Riding of Yorkshire|West Riding]] of [[Yorkshire]], England, from 1835 to 1974.<ref name=vision_cb>{{cite vob | url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10108809&c_id=10001043 | name=Leeds MB/CB | accessdate=2009-09-16}}</ref> It originated from the ancient borough of [[Leeds]], which was reformed by the [[Municipal Corporations Act 1835]]. In 1889, when [[West Riding of Yorkshire|West Riding County Council]] was formed, Leeds became a [[County Borough]] outside the administrative county of the West Riding; and in 1893 the borough gained [[City status in the United Kingdom|city status]]. The borough was extended a number of times, expanding from {{convert|21593|acres|km2}} in 1911 to {{convert|40612|acres|km2}} in 1961; adding in stages the former area of Roundhay, Seacroft, Shadwell and Middleton parishes and gaining other parts of adjacent districts. In 1971 Leeds was the fifth largest [[List of administrative counties and county boroughs of England by population in 1971|county borough by population]] in England. The county borough was abolished in 1974 and replaced with the larger [[City of Leeds]], a [[metropolitan borough|metropolitan district]] of [[West Yorkshire]].
{{TOClimit|2}}
==Origins==
===Manorial borough 1207&ndash;1662===
The [[Borough]] of [[Leeds]] was created in 1207, when Maurice Paynel, [[Lord of the Manor]], granted a [[charter]] to the inhabitants of the town of Leeds. They were created "[[Burgess (title)|burgesses]]", and were given the right to hold half an [[acre]] of land, trade as they liked, and transport their goods by land or water, subject to [[Tariff|tolls]] and restrictions paid to the manor. The only officer of the borough was a [[praetor]], appointed annually at the [[Feast of Pentecost]] by the Lord of the Borough. The praetor had the duty of administering justice and collecting fines and other revenues.<ref name=relics/> The borough formed only a small area adjacent to a crossing of the [[River Aire]], between the old settlement centred on [[Leeds Parish Church]] to the east and the manor house and mills to the west.<ref name=fraser1>{{cite book |title=A History of Modern Leeds |editor-last=Fraser |editor-first=Derek |last=Forster |first=G C E |chapter=The foundation: from the earliest times to c. 1700 |year=1980 |publisher=[[Manchester University Press]] |location=Manchester |isbn=071900781X |oclc= |page= |pages=5-6 |url= }} </ref> The borough consisted of a single street with approximately thirty [[burgage plot]]s.<ref name=fraser1/>  By the seventeenth century the title of praetor had been abandoned in favour of the more customary "[[bailiff]]", but otherwise the government of the town remained in the form introduced in the thirteenth century. An enquiry into the administration of local charities in 1620 disclosed that many of the funds were diverted by the bailiff for his private use. This, and other irregularities, led the inhabitants of Leeds to petition [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] for a [[royal charter|charter of incorporation]].<ref name=relics>{{cite book |title=Relics of Old Leeds |last=Robinson |first=Percy |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1896 |publisher=B T Batsford |location=London |isbn= |oclc= |page= |pages=9-17 |url= |accessdate=}} </ref>

===Incorporated borough 1626&ndash;1836===
====Incorporation====
A charter of incorporation was granted on 13 July 1626, incorporating the entire parish of Leeds St Peter as the "Borough of Leedes in the County of York". The parish and borough consisted of eleven chapelries ([[Armley]], [[Beeston, Leeds|Beeston]], [[Beeston, Leeds|Bramley]], [[Chapel Allerton]], [[Farnley, West Yorkshire|Farnley]], [[Headingley cum Burley]], [[Holbeck]], [[Hunslet]], [[Leeds]], [[Potternewton]] and [[Wortley, West Yorkshire|Wortley]]) and parts of two more ([[Seacroft]] and [[Temple Newsam]]).<ref name=vision_parish>{{cite vob | url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10443337 | name=Leeds parish | | accessdate=2009-09-16}}</ref> 

The governing corporation of the borough was styled "The Alderman and Burgesses of the Borough of Leedes in the County of York", and consisted of one [[Alderman]], nine principal burgesses and twenty assistants. The charter named the members of the first corporation, with Sir John Savile becoming the first alderman.<ref name=lewis>{{cite web |title=Leeds (St. Peter) |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=51100#s23 |date=1848 |work=A Topographical Dictionary of England | author=Samuel Lewis (editor) |publisher=British History Online |accessdate=22 September 2009}}</ref><ref name=relics/><ref name=leeds>{{cite web |title=Historical notes |url=http://www.leeds.gov.uk/files/2005/week47/inter__79A23928963937DC80256E160032DB3C_ce625ffb-1cce-4c93-bf85-8afb93573e25.pdf |date= |format=PDF |work= |publisher=[[Leeds City Council]] |accessdate=22 September 2009}}</ref>

====Charter of Charles II====
In January 1643, during the [[English Civil War]], Leeds fell to [[New Model Army|parliamentary forces]]. Royalist members of the corporation were replaced with those loyal to the Commonwealth. With the restoration of the monarchy in 1660, moves were made to reform the borough's government. The leading merchants of the town submitted a petition to [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] requesting a new charter as they felt the constitution and operation of the governing body was inadequate to the needs of the town.<ref name=relics/> 

A second charter was duly granted on 2 November 1661, with the earlier charter withdrawn.<ref name=lewis/><ref name=relics/><ref name=leeds/> The new corporation thus created consisted of a [[mayor]], twelve [[alderman|aldermen]], twenty four assistants,  a [[recorder (judge)|recorder]] and a [[town clerk]] and was entitled the "Mayor, Aldermen and Burgesses of the Borough of Leedes in the County of York".  The charter named the first mayor as Thomas Danby.<ref name=leeds/><ref name=lewis/><ref name=relics/> The new corporation was given extensive powers to enforce and make laws to regulate trade and ensure the good governance of the town.<ref name=relics/> From 1684 to 1689 the town was governed under a charter of [[James II of England|James II]] which gave the crown power over all appointments to the town council. With the accession of [[William III of England|William III]] and [[Mary II of England|Mary II]] the 1661 charter was restored to the townspeople, and remained the governing charter until 1836.<ref name=relics/>

==Municipal borough 1836 &ndash; 1889==

In 1833 the [[Whig (British political faction)|Whig]] Government of [[Charles Grey, 2nd Earl Grey|Lord Grey]] began enquiries into the government of the various boroughs in England and Wales, with a view to reforming their constitutions and methods of election.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1833/feb/14/corporations#S3V0015P0_18330214_HOC_20 |title=Corporations |accessdate=2009-02-19 |work=Hansard 1803 - 2005 |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |date=14 February 1833 }}</ref> Following the recommendations of a [[Royal Commission]], legislation was enacted as the [[Municipal Corporations Act 1835]]. 

Leeds was among the 178 boroughs reformed by the act, becoming the "Municipal Borough of Leeds". The reformed borough was initially unchanged in area, and was divided into 12 [[ward (politics)|wards]], with a town council of 16 aldermen and 48 councillors, headed by a mayor.<ref> Municipal Corporations Act, 1835 (5 & 6 Will. 4 c. 76), Sch. A</ref> Each ward was represented by either three or six directly elected councillors. One third of the councillors retired annually. Aldermen were additional members of the council, there being one alderman for every three councillors: they had a six-year term of office, with half of the aldermanic bench elected by the council itself every three years. 
